<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><b><i><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><a
href="statevnations.html">State v. Nations</a></span></i></b><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>A
16-year-old girl was found dancing at a club.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>Cops approached the defendant and asked her about the girl�s age.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The defendant claimed that she had checked,
but she hadn�t.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>She is convicted of
child endangerment.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Nations
claims the defense that the state must prove that she <i>knew</i> the girl was
underage.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>In </span><st1:State><st1:place><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Missouri</span></st1:place></st1:State><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>, knowledge means <i>awareness</i>
of facts; here we�re talking about knowledge of an attendant circumstance.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>This is not the Model Penal Code formulation.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
court says that the Model Penal Code is the source for the Missouri Criminal
Code.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>If this were a Model Penal Code
case, how could the prosecutor strengthen the argument that Nations did what
she did <i>knowingly</i>?<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Model Penal
Code � 2.02(7) tells us that �wilful blindness� is tantamount to knowledge.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>In
the Model Penal Code, if the issue is whether a defendant had knowledge of an
attendant circumstance, you must study Model Penal Code � 2.02(2)(b)(i), which
looks a whole lot like the </span><st1:State><st1:place><span style='font-size:
  14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Missouri</span></st1:place></st1:State><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'> statute.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>But then you have to add on � 2.02(7), which
adds to the meaning of the term �knowledge�.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span></span><st1:State><st1:place><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
  12.0pt'>Missouri</span></st1:place></st1:State><span style='font-size:14.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'> finds that the Model Penal Code is the source for
their code, however, the legislature of </span><st1:State><st1:place><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Missouri</span></st1:place></st1:State><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'> did not choose to include
the �wilful blindness� provision in their version of the Code.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Why
did the Model Penal Code add this provision?<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>We want to be able to hold people responsible for deliberately shielding
themselves from knowledge that would otherwise go towards proving an offense.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>We
want to prevent the �ostrich phenomenon�.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>This is especially important for prosecutors of white collar crime
cases.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The higher-ups will protect
themselves by prosecution by avoiding knowing the offenses being done to try to
avoid prosecution.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>However, the �wilful
blindness� provision makes it less likely this stratagem will succeed.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>What
argument can be put forward again this �wilful blindness� provision?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>It blurs the like between knowledge and
recklessness.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>What is the mental state
of a person who is aware of a high probability that, for example, a female
dancer is under the age of 17?<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Isn�t
that very similar to the definition of recklessness, which talks about
disregarding a substantial and unjustifiable risk?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Many critics say this provision is no good
because it defies understanding what it means to �know� something when in fact
you <i>don�t </i>know it.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>If,
on the other hand, you require <i>actual</i> knowledge, as in </span><st1:State><st1:place><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Missouri</span></st1:place></st1:State><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>, it will be harder to get
convictions in cases like this.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>We could
attack this two ways: we could knock down the standard of culpability in the
statute to recklessness, or else you can, by statute, ratchet up the mental
state of �wilful blindness� to knowledge, as the Model Penal Code does.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
court makes a mistake in this case.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>It
reverses the terms in the Model Penal Code in an inappropriate way: the court
says that there must be a �high probability� that the defendant was aware,
whereas the Model Penal Code says that the defendant must be aware of a �high
