<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><b><i><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><a
href="peoplevnavarro.html">People v. Navarro</a></span></i></b><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Navarro
took some wooden beams, mistakenly believing they were abandoned.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>This is a common claim made by defendants: a <i>mistake
of fact</i>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Navarro
wants a certain jury instruction that basically says if he made a good faith
mistake he should be acquitted, even if it was entirely unreasonable.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The judge did not accept this jury
instruction, but rather told the jury to acquit only if the mistake was
reasonable.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
appellate court says that the defendant�s instruction was correct.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>If
the belief was unreasonable, did he act in a morally culpable manner?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>We would more or less be saying he was
negligent.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>There would be a <i>mens rea</i>,
and thus <i>some</i> level of culpability.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>Why did the court reverse the verdict?<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>He lacked the specific intent required for the crime.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Moral culpability is general intent.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>What
would Model Penal Code � 2.04 say about this case?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>It says either the mistake does or does not
negate the required <i>mens rea</i> for the crime.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>If the <i>mens rea</i> is the �intent� or
�purpose� to steal, and the mistake proves that the defendant did not have such
a purpose, then the defendant must be acquitted.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The Model Penal Code rules!<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>�Mistake
of fact� is not a true affirmative defense.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>It is really a challenge to proof beyond a reasonable doubt of <i>mens
rea</i>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
handout on mistake of fact analysis</span></b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
first thing to do when you�re in a non-Model Penal Code jurisdiction is to ask:
is it a general intent, specific intent, or strict liability crime?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>If it�s strict liability, you�re done.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Intent doesn�t matter, and thus mistake
doesn�t matter.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>If
you have a specific intent crime, you ask if the mistake relates to the
specific intent portion of the crime.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>In
the case of Navarro, his mistake directly relates to his intent to steal.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>This being the case, we use the so-called
�elemental� analysis.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Does Navarro�s
mistake of fact negate the specific intent element of the offense?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>In this case, we may well argue that it does.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>If
you have a general intent crime, then at common law you must apply a
�culpability� analysis.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>You must ask
whether the defendant�s state of mind was blameworthy, and in particular you
must ask whether or not their mistake, and in turn their behavior, was
reasonable.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>This
is complicated!!!<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The Model Penal Code
is better, Dressler thinks!<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>In the Model
Penal Code, you <i>always</i> apply �elemental� analysis.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><b><i><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Regina
v. Prince</span></i></b><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
12.0pt'> and the �moral wrong� doctrine<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Prince
believed the girl he was taking away was 18, but she was really 14.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The jury found that his mistake was
reasonable.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
court takes the offense to be a general intent crime.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>A reasonable mistake means there is no
culpability.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>However, the conviction was
upheld.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Why?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Taking an 18 year old away from her parents
was considered immoral.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>When
you use the �moral wrong� doctrine, you look at the world through the eyes of
the defendant and assume the facts as the defendant himself understood
them.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>This doctrine says that if the
defendant acted immorally, it is reasonable for him to assume the risk that the
circumstances are different from what he thinks they are and thus be found
guilty of some crime.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Here, we end up
asking: are you a bad guy?<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The answer
turns out to be yes, even though there is a reasonable mistake of fact.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Many
jurisdictions do not apply this doctrine anymore.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>It is a position that some jurisdictions
still do use.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>What�s wrong with this
doctrine?<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>One
issue is: how do we determine that certain conduct is immoral?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Basically, judges will decide.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>In </span><st1:country-region><st1:place><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>England</span></st1:place></st1:country-region><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'> in 1875, it was probably
uncontroversial that an 18-year-old should not be taken from her parents.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>In the </span><st1:country-region><st1:place><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>United States</span></st1:place></st1:country-region><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>, however, we have a much
greater diversity of viewpoints.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
other problem is the principle of legality.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>If it�s so wrong to take an 18-year-old away from her parents, make it a
crime!<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>There�s a lack of notice and the
risk of the court creating crimes.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>We
do not live in a world where everything that is immoral is illegal.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>There are lots of things that people do that
are immoral that are not a crime.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>It is
up to the legislature to draw a line between the illegal and the merely
immoral.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>This
is a very controversial doctrine, but it�s out there, and sometimes it �bites
you� when you least expect it.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Hypothetical:
battery upon a police officer</span></b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Say
you apply the �moral wrong� doctrine to this situation.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Is it morally wrong for someone to push
someone they believe is attacking her?<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>No, so under this doctrine she is acquitted because through her eyes, she
was acting in self-defense.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Hypothetical:
