<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:Arial'>The text states that Frank started to act �just as a man who
falls into the fire begins to act� and �the gun sprang to his shoulder�.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Frank may argue that this tends to show that
he did not act voluntarily.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Note
that in 99.9% of all cases, there is a voluntary act.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>But there will be a few cases where you can
make an argument to the contrary.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Are
there always two sides to every argument?<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>No, not <i>always</i>.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>A lawyer has
to spot the <i>real</i> issues that he must be prepared to argue.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>If there is an argument for the other side,
you must be ready, having already thought of it yourself.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>On the other hand, you can�t go making up
