<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Criminal
law is, in a sense, a morality play, especially in cases like this.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The jury represents the community�s
values.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>They represent the judgment of
the community as to whether the defendant�s conduct is right or wrong, above
and beyond whether the defendant should be punished.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
women�s groups told the lawyer that they wouldn�t pay him unless he would plead
self-defense.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>That�s a conflict of
interest.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The attorney considered doing
self-defense, but didn�t.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Later cases,
like <i>Norman</i>, tried the self-defense route.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Pretend
we don�t know of battered woman syndrome.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>Forget the law.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Do we justify her
conduct?<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Do we excuse her conduct?<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>One
theory is that Mr. Norman did not deserve to live.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>That�s the moral forfeiture theory.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>What if he gets killed by a hit man?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Dressler suggests that if you follow the
moral forfeiture theory where it morally takes you, there must be no social
harm in taking Mr. Norman�s life and thus no principled reason that it�s not
okay for Judy or anyone else to do it.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Another
theory is the moral rights theory.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
Model Penal Code formulation of self-defense<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
Model Penal Code doesn�t focus on the amount of time before the actor will be
killed, rather, it focuses on the actor to figure out if it is necessary <i>now</i>
to use deadly force against the victim.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Say
Mr. Norman tells Mrs. Norman she�s going to leave the room and get a gun to
kill her.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Under common law, Mrs. Norman
is defenseless until Mr. Norman actually gets the gun and points it at
her.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>However, under the Model Penal
Code, she would be justified in killing Mr. Norman before he gets the gun if
she believes he�s going to kill her soon.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Even
if there�s no battered woman syndrome, the fact that Mrs. Norman is a battered
woman arguably should be admitted into evidence.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>The fact that she�s been beat up a lot makes
her belief system more reasonable.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>The
law treats human life as almost <i>sanctified</i>.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>It doesn�t want innocent people to kill even <i>bad
guys</i> unless absolutely necessary.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>�
</span>That�s why there�s just a strong requirement that the threat to the
defender be <i>imminent</i>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Compare
to the situation with </span><st1:country-region><st1:place><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Iraq</span></st1:place></st1:country-region><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>�is pre-emption ever
justified?<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>� </span>Or was the threat framed as
imminent?<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>Does
syndrome evidence arguably turn a justification defense into an excuse?<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'>When
we get in to the excuse defenses: are there any excuses that could be used to
excuse Judy Norman?<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

